      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Negotiate an Early Lease Break With Your Tenant Before Selling in Brisbane
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        You want to sell with vacant possession. Your tenant is mid-lease. Here is what the law allows, how to approach the conversation, and when it makes more sense to sell with the tenant in place.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the more delicate situations a property investor faces is wanting to sell while a tenant is partway through a fixed-term lease. The instinct is often to wait until the lease expires naturally, but that can mean holding a property for months you did not plan to. The alternative, negotiating an early exit with the tenant, is possible and often successful if approached correctly. But it has to be handled carefully, and it has to respect what the law actually permits.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers sometimes want vacant possession</h2>
      <p>Vacant properties are almost always easier to present, style, and show than tenanted ones. Without furniture constraints, a stylist can compose each room to appeal to the broadest possible buyer. Open homes run more smoothly when the property is empty and the agent has full control of access. And some buyers, particularly owner-occupiers who want to move in after settlement, either strongly prefer or outright require vacant possession. In Brisbane's inner-east suburbs, where the owner-occupier buyer pool is dominant, this preference is particularly pronounced.</p>

      <p>There is also the practical point that tenants, even cooperative ones, create access complexity. They have rights around inspection frequency, notice periods, and the condition in which the property must be left. A vacant property removes those variables entirely and gives the campaign cleaner execution.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the law says in Queensland</h2>
      <p>This is where sellers sometimes get into trouble. Under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (Qld), a landlord cannot unilaterally end a fixed-term tenancy early. The fact that you want to sell is not a legal ground for termination during a fixed term. The tenant has a contractual right to occupy the property for the term of their lease, and neither party can simply walk away from that agreement without the other's consent.</p>

      <p>If the tenant refuses to end the lease early, you cannot force them out before the fixed term expires, regardless of whether you have a contract of sale. The exception is a situation where the contract of sale specifically requires vacant possession at settlement and settlement is imminent, at which point proper notice provisions apply. But even then, the process requires following the Act's notice requirements, and the timeline must be realistic. You cannot sign a contract with a 30-day settlement and expect a tenant to vacate in that window without their agreement.</p>

      <p>For periodic tenancies (month-to-month), the rules are different. A landlord can issue a notice to leave to a periodic tenant who has a contract of sale in place, with a minimum notice period of four weeks. But fixed-term leases are a different matter entirely.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to approach the conversation with your tenant</h2>
      <p>The most effective lease break negotiations start with honesty and respect. Tenants who feel ambushed or pressured are far less likely to cooperate than those who feel genuinely informed and considered. Contact your tenant directly, or through your property manager, as early as possible. Explain that you are planning to sell and that you would like to discuss whether there is an arrangement that works for both parties.</p>

      <p>Give them time to respond and to think about their own situation. Many tenants, particularly those who have been renting for several years, are open to the idea of moving on, especially if they are given adequate notice and a financial incentive that makes the transition genuinely worthwhile. The worst approach is to spring it on them with a short deadline and an inadequate offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is a fair financial incentive</h2>
      <p>There is no formula that works in every case, but a reasonable starting point is to think about what it actually costs a tenant to leave before their lease ends. That includes moving costs, the inconvenience of finding a new property in what is often a competitive rental market, and the possibility that the rent they will pay elsewhere is higher than what they are currently paying. A fair incentive covers those real costs and acknowledges the disruption.</p>

      <p>Common approaches include a rent reduction for the remaining term (for example, the tenant pays no rent for their last six weeks in exchange for vacating two months early), or a cash payment equivalent to four to eight weeks of their current rent, depending on how much of their lease remains. In a tight rental market, where a tenant might need to pay significantly more per week for a comparable property, the incentive needs to reflect that premium.</p>

      <p>The framing matters too. Presenting it as a mutual arrangement, rather than a favour you are asking for or something the tenant is obligated to consider, tends to produce better outcomes. You are offering them something in exchange for something, and that is a negotiation, not a demand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Document everything in writing</h2>
      <p>Any agreement to end a fixed-term tenancy early must be in writing and signed by both parties. A verbal agreement is not enforceable, and relying on one puts you in a difficult position if the tenant later changes their mind or there is a dispute about what was agreed. Your property manager should prepare a mutual termination agreement that records the agreed end date, any financial arrangement, and the condition requirements for vacating.</p>

      <p>It is also worth having your property manager review any documentation before it is signed. A poorly worded agreement can create ambiguity about notice periods, bond returns, or whether the financial incentive constitutes a variation to the original lease. Get it right the first time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the tenant says no</h2>
      <p>If the tenant declines your offer, or declines to engage at all, your options are limited. You cannot pressure them, reduce services, or create conditions that make the tenancy unpleasant in order to encourage them to leave. Those approaches violate the tenant's rights and can expose you to a tribunal complaint. The realistic options are to improve your offer, wait for the fixed term to expire, or sell the property with the tenant in place.</p>

      <p>Selling tenanted is not necessarily a worse outcome. It simply means targeting a different buyer pool, primarily investors rather than owner-occupiers. If the property has a good rental history and a reliable tenant on a reasonable rent, that is a genuine selling point to an investor buyer who does not need to source a tenant themselves. Your agent should be able to tell you what the investor demand looks like for your property type in your suburb right now.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The alternative: sell with the tenant in place</h2>
      <p>In some situations, particularly where the rental return is strong and the tenant is well-established, selling with a tenant in place is genuinely the better strategy. An investor buyer purchasing a property with a quality tenant already secured avoids the vacancy risk and the cost of finding and vetting a new tenant. That certainty has value, and a skilled agent can position it accordingly.</p>

      <p>The key question is whether the value you lose by selling to an investor-only pool, rather than the full market including owner-occupiers, outweighs the cost and complexity of negotiating a lease break. In most inner-east Brisbane suburbs, owner-occupiers tend to pay more than investors for comparable properties, so the calculation often favours negotiating vacant possession if it can be done reasonably. But it is a case-by-case assessment, and your agent should be able to give you a clear view of what the numbers actually look like for your property.</p>

